  "issue_title": "feature: add Android target selector model",
  "issue_body": "Parent: #75\n\n## Problem\n\nTouchPilot tools currently pass target data as loose arguments such as `text`, `node_id`, or `bounds`. That makes tool behavior harder to validate, rank, debug, and extend.\n\n## Proposed behavior\n\nAdd a stable target selector model for Android UI targets.\n\nThe selector should support:\n\n- `text`\n- `contentDescription`\n- `nodeId`\n- `bounds`\n- `viewIdResourceName`\n- optional role/package/window metadata\n- confidence/source metadata for resolver output\n\n## User workflow\n\nWhen the agent or local router chooses a UI target, TouchPilot should represent the target in one structured shape before execution.\n\n## Local-first impact\n\nA local agent needs deterministic, inspectable target data. This selector model becomes the contract between screen understanding, routing, and Android tool execution.\n\n## Safety and security considerations\n\nSelectors must be redacted in logs when they contain sensitive text. The model should make ambiguity explicit rather than encouraging blind taps.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n- [ ] Add a structured selector model for Android targets.\n- [ ] Support current `tap` selectors: text, node id, and bounds.\n- [ ] Include view id/content description fields for future resolver work.\n- [ ] Add unit tests for selector construction and redaction-sensitive fields where practical.\n- [ ] Do not change runtime tool behavior in this PR unless necessary.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\nKeep loose string maps. Rejected because Milestone 4 needs stronger validation, ranking, and verification contracts.\n",
